special edition page 1 special edition september 1 2009 from the stanford bargaining team welcome to a special edition of the stanford seiu bargaining update in connection with stanford university's contract negotiations with the service employees international union local 2007 seiu on july 7 2009 stanford and seiu began negotiations for a new collective bargaining agreement for approximately 1200 employees in schools and departments across the university including the slac national laboratory this update available during these negotiations provides information about ideas and interests discussed options tentatively agreed to or other outcomes please disseminate the update as needed special edition stanford and the seiu reach tentative agreement on a new contract after eight weeks of negotiations stanford and the seiu have reached tentative agreement on a new five year contract which once ratified will strengthen the organization by helping us continue to operate important university functions in a sustainable way the seiu bargaining team has agreed to recommend the contract to its membership for ratification which is scheduled to take place this thursday september 3 2009 highlights of the tentative agreement a responsible wage package provides an approximate 12.5 increase 0 yr 1 2 yr 2 3 yr 3 3.5 yr 4 4 yr 5 in wages over five years and establishes a more competitive and viable future for many important stanford operations a reformed step progression structure modifies the step progression structure from 5 steps with 4.5 over 5 wage increments between the steps to a new 10 step structure with approximately 2.1 increases between each step established a more competitive grounds unit reached agreement to transition some workers to an outside landscape contractor coupled with wage reductions and new more competitive wage classifications language clarification modifies language regarding family medical leave so that it is consistent with university policy and the law page 2 special edition september 1 2009 codified the use of temporary workers agreed to include contract language that provides management flexibility regarding the use of temporary workers an agreement which was previously stated in a side letter consistent severance policy establishes a severance policy which creates consistency with the university policy new language regarding alternative work schedules and apprenticeships provides a framework that establishes the rules which govern the institution of alternative work schedules such as 4 10s and apprenticeship opportunities that arise contract term september 1 2009 august 31 2014 the stanford bargaining team the stanford bargaining team includes david a jones director employee & management services human resources ann allison marsh senior manager employee & labor relations human resources cori bossenberry director of human resources school of medicine robert carpenter director of operations buildings and grounds maintenance land buildings and real estate megan davis associate vice president finance land buildings and real estate eric montell executive director stanford dining residential and dining enterprises and larry young director of human resources slac national laboratory
